
The Data Layer : 

The Data Layer. Your microservices for CloudBite cannot function without a place to store state and data.

We will use Terraform to declare this infrastructure. We are going to start by provisioning the DynamoDB Global Table which will act as the ultra-fast, multi-region cache for your user sessions and active food carts.

Step 1: Set up the workspace

Create a new directory  for your database infrastructure and navigate into it

>> mkdir cloudbite-global-data
>> cd cloudbite-global-data

Step 2: The provider configuration (provider.tf)

Because we are building a multi-region architecture ,we have to tell terraform how to talk to both regions .Create a file named provider.tf and paste this in : 

terraform{
  required_provider  {
    aws = {
      source = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "~>5.0"
    }
  }
}
#Primary region

provider "aws"{
  region = "ap-south-1"
  alias = "primary"
}

# secondary / DR region 

provider "aws"{
  region = "ap-southeast-1"
  alias = "secondary"
}



dynamodb.tf

resource "aws_dynamodb_table" "cloudbite_sessions"{
  provider = aws.primary 
  name = "cloudbite-user-sessions"
  billing_mode = "PAY_PER_REQUEST"
  hash_key = "SessionId"
  
  deletion_protection_enabled = true
  attribute {
    name = "SessionId"
    type = "S"
  }
  point_in_time_recovery {
    enabled = true
  }
  
  stream_enabled = true  
  stream_view_type = "NEW_AND_OLD_IMAGES"
  
  replica {
    region_name = "ap-southeast-1"
    propogate_tags = true
    point_in_time_recovery = true
  }
  ttl {
    attribute_name = "Expiration_time"
    enabled = true
  }
  server_side_encryption {
    enable = true
  }
  tags = {
    Environment = "Production"
    Project     = "CloudBite"
    Component   = "StateDatabase"
  }

    
}

Now we deploy this to your AWS account .Run these commands in your terminal one by one:

terraform init
terraform plan
terraform apply

While that deploys, you will have a globally replicated, serverless database that scales infinitely without you ever having to manage a server.




Amazon Aurora PostgreSQL  Global Database.

For CloudBite's core transactional data—like final order receipts, user profiles, and payment statuses—DynamoDB isn't enough. We need strict ACID compliance (so nobody gets double-charged) but with the ability to survive a region-wide failure.

An Aurora Global Database spans multiple AWS regions. It uses dedicated AWS infrastructure to replicate your data from the primary region to the secondary region with less than 1 second of lag. If your primary region goes down, the secondary region can be promoted to full read/write capacity in under a minute.

Here is the terrform configuration .Create a new file name aurora.tf

# The Global RDS Cluster Object 
# This acts as the container for cross - region replication 

resource "aws_rds_global_cluster" "cloudbite_global" {
  provider = aws.primary 
  global_cluster_identifier = "cloudbite-global-db"
  engine = "aurora-postgresql"
  engine_version = "15.4"
  database_name = "cloudbite_core"
  storage_encrypted = true
}

# The primary Database cluster (main region - ap-south-1)

resource "aws_rds_cluster" "primary" {
  provider = aws.primary 
  engine = aws_rds_global_cluster.cloudbite_global.engine
  engine_version = aws_rds_global_cluster.cloudbite_global.engine_version
  cluster_identifier = "cloudbite-primary-cluster"
  global_cluster_identifier = aws_rds_global_cluster.cloudbite_global.id
  
  
  master_username = "dbadmin"
  master_password = "SuperSecretPassword123!"
  
  backup_retention_pretection = 14
  preferred_backup_window = "02:00-03:00"
  storage_encrypted = true 
  deletion_protection = true
  skip_final_snapshot = false 
}


# Primary cluster compute Instance (multi-az for local high availability )\

resource " aws_rds_cluster_instance" "primary_instances" {
  provider = aws.primary 
  count  = 2 
  identifier = "cloudbite-primary-instance-${count.index + 1}"
  cluster_identifier = aws_rds_cluster.primary.id
  instance_class = "db.r6g.large"
  engine = aws__rds_cluster.primary.engine
  engine_version  = aws_rds_cluster.primary.engine_version
}

resource "aws_rds_cluster" "secondary" {
  provider = aws.secondary
  engine = aws_rds_global_cluster.cloudbite_global.engine
  engine_verison = aws_rds_global_cluster.cloudbite_global.engine_version
  cluster_identifier = "cloudbite-secondary-cluster"
  global_cluster_identifiere = aws_rds_global_cluster.cloudbite_global.id
  

  storage_encrypted = true
  skip_final_snapshot = true
 
  depends_on = [
    aws_rds_cluster_instance.primary_instances
  ]
}

resource "aws_rds_cluster_instance" "secondary_instance" {
  provider = aws.secondary
  count                = 1 # Only 1 instance needed here until a disaster occurs
  identifier           = "cloudbite-secondary-instance-${count.index + 1}"
  cluster_identifier   = aws_rds_cluster.secondary.id
  instance_class       = "db.r6g.large"
  engine               = aws_rds_cluster.secondary.engine
  engine_version       = aws_rds_cluster.secondary.engine_version
}


Key enterprise feature : 

Global Inheritance: The secondary cluster doesn't have a master username or password block. It natively syncs all security credentials and schema data from the global object.

Asymmetrical Compute: Notice the count parameters. The primary cluster has count = 2 (running in Multi-AZ for high availability during normal traffic). The secondary cluster has count = 1 because it is just a "Warm Standby" receiving replication data. You don't need to pay for 2 instances in the DR region unless a disaster actually happens (at which point you scale it up).

Storage Encryption & Deletion Protection: Both are hardcoded to true to ensure the data cannot be read without KMS keys and the cluster cannot be wiped out by a fat-fingered CLI command.


