The compute layer 

While the Terraform is fantastic  for static infrastructure like datbase ,managing the intricate  web of IAM roles  ,security groups and VPC configuration required  for  a kubernetes control plane via Terraform can quickly become a nightmare 



Instead, DevOps engineers use eksctl, the official CLI tool developed by AWS and Weaveworks. You define the entire cluster in a single, readable YAML file, and eksctl automatically translates it into AWS CloudFormation templates to build the network, the control plane, and the worker nodes safely.

Let's write the cluster configuration file. Create a file named cloudbite-cluster.yaml.

The Production-Grade EKS Configuration (cloudbite-cluster.yaml)
This configuration does three critical things for a production environment:

1.Spans 3 Availability Zones: For absolute high availability.
2.Enables IAM OIDC Provider: This is a massive security upgrade. It allows your individual microservices (Pods) to assume IAM roles. Instead of giving the entire EC2 server permission to read DynamoDB, you only give permission to the specific Node.js pod that needs it.
3.Bootstraps a Managed Node Group: This provisions our baseline compute capacity so the cluster has somewhere to run our core system controllers (like ArgoCD and the Ingress controller).


cloudbite-cluster.yaml

apiVersion: eksctl.io/v1alpha5
kind: ClusterConfig

metadata: 
  name: cloudbite-production-cluster
  region: ap-south-1
  version: "1.29"
  tags: 
    Environment: Production 
    Project: Cloudbite
  
vpc: 
  subnets:
    private: 
      ap-south-1a: { id: subnet-0123456789abcdef0}
      ap-south-1b: { id:  subnet-0123456789abcdef0}
      ap-south-1d { id : subnet-0123456789abcdef0 }
iam: 
  withOIDC: true
  serviceAccounts: 
  #  Pre-configuring the IAM role for the AWS loadbalancer controller we will install later 
    - metadata: 
        name: aws-load-balancer-controller
        namespace: kube-system
      wellknowPolicies: 
        awsLoadBalancerController: true
   

How to Deploy the Cluster
Once you have saved that file (and updated the subnet IDs to match the VPC you would have created), you run a single command in your terminal:


>> eksctl create cluster -f cloudbite-cluster.yaml


What happens next:
Go grab a coffee. EKS clusters take roughly 15 to 20 minutes to provision. eksctl is working in the background to:

1.Spin up the highly available Kubernetes control plane (managed by AWS).
2.Create the EC2 Auto Scaling Group for your t3.large worker nodes.
3.Securely join those worker nodes to the cluster.
4.Automatically update your local ~/.kube/config file so your terminal can talk to the new cluster.


Verfiying the build : 

Once the command finishes, you can verify your cluster is alive and communicating by running:

kubectl get nodes

YOu should see 3 nodesw in Ready state



The production VPC terraform code (vpc.tf)

We willuse the official AWS VPC terraform module . It handels all the complex route tabel ,NAT gateways and EKS tagging automatically 

Create file named VPC.tf in your terraform directory and paste this code

module "vpc" {
  source  = "terraform-aws-modules/vpc/aws"
  version = "~> 5.0"

  name = "cloudbite-production-vpc"
  cidr = "10.0.0.0/16"

  # 3 Availability Zones for High Availability
  azs             = ["ap-south-1a", "ap-south-1b", "ap-south-1c"]
  
  # Private subnets for your EKS Worker Nodes and Pods
  private_subnets = ["10.0.1.0/24", "10.0.2.0/24", "10.0.3.0/24"]
  
  # Public subnets strictly for your ALBs and NAT Gateways
  public_subnets  = ["10.0.101.0/24", "10.0.102.0/24", "10.0.103.0/24"]

  # Production NAT Gateway Setup (1 per AZ for true high availability)
  enable_nat_gateway     = true
  single_nat_gateway     = false 
  one_nat_gateway_per_az = true

  enable_dns_hostnames = true
  enable_dns_support   = true

  # CRITICAL: These tags are required for the AWS Load Balancer Controller to work
  public_subnet_tags = {
    "kubernetes.io/role/elb" = 1
  }

  private_subnet_tags = {
    "kubernetes.io/role/internal-elb" = 1
  }

  tags = {
    Environment = "Production"
    Project     = "CloudBite"
  }
}

# Output the private subnet IDs so we can copy them into our eksctl yaml
output "eks_private_subnets" {
  value = module.vpc.private_subnets
}  

The workflow 
1.You run  terraform apply on this vpc.tf file
2.TErraform builds your highly available network 
3.At the end.TErraform outputs your three private subnets ID's
4.You copy those three ID's paste them into the cloudbite-cluster.yaml file we wrote earlier
5.Then you run eksctl create cluster -f cloudbite-cluster.yaml

This guarantees your EKS cluster boots up inside a rock-solid, production-ready network foundation.


This phase is where we install the AWS Load Balancer Controller using Helm. This controller is the "brain" that lives inside your cluster, constantly watching for new microservices. When you eventually deploy the frontend for CloudBite, this controller is what will dynamically spin up an Application Load Balancer in those public subnets we just built and route the traffic directly to your Pod IPs.

Here is how you install it : 

Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes (think of it like npm for Node.js or pip for Python). We need to tell Helm where to find the official AWS controller packages.


Step 2: Install the Controller

Because we were smart and used eksctl in the previous phase to pre-create the IAM role and the Kubernetes Service Account (aws-load-balancer-controller), this installation is incredibly clean. We just have to tell Helm to use the Service Account that already exists.

helm install aws-load-balancer-controller eks/aws-load-balancer-controller \
  -n kube-system \
  --set clusterName=cloudbite-production-cluster \
  --set serviceAccount.create=false \
  --set serviceAccount.name=aws-load-balancer-controller

Step 3: Verify the Installation
It takes a few seconds for the pods to spin up. You can check if the controller is running successfully by asking kubectl to show you the pods in that namespace:

kubectl get pods -n kube-system | grep aws-load-balancer-controller

Once those pods are alive, your Kubernetes cluster is officially physically connected to your AWS networking layer. It is now capable of exposing your applications to the public internet securely!



