Gitops 

With GitOps, your GitHub repository becomes the single source of truth. ArgoCD lives inside your EKS cluster, constantly watching your food_booking_app repository. If it detects a change in your code (e.g., you pushed a new image tag for the FastAPI Search or Flask Recommender microservice), ArgoCD automatically pulls the new manifest and syncs the live cluster to match it.


Here is how we install and configure the continuous deployment engine.

Step 1: Install ArgoCD into the EKS Cluster

We will create a dedicated namespace for ArgoCD and install it using its official manifest. Run these commands in your terminal:


kubectl create namespace argocd
kubectl apply -n argocd -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj/argo-cd/stable/manifests/install.yaml


kubectl get pods -n argocd


Step 2: Define the CloudBite Application
Now we need to tell ArgoCD exactly where your Kubernetes YAML files live. We do this by creating a Custom Resource Definition (CRD) called an Application.


Create a file named cloudbite-argocd-app.yaml and paste the following configuration. This assumes you keep your Kubernetes deployment files in a folder called k8s-manifests inside your repository.


apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: cloudbite-production
  namespace: argocd
spec:
  project: default
  source:
    # The repository containing your multi-stage Dockerfiles and k8s manifests
    repoURL: 'https://github.com/your-username/food_booking_app.git'
    path: k8s-manifests
    targetRevision: HEAD
  destination:
    # Deploying to the same cluster ArgoCD is running in
    server: 'https://kubernetes.default.svc'
    namespace: production
  
  # The Magic: GitOps Automation
  syncPolicy:
    automated:
      prune: true     # Automatically delete pods if you remove them from Git
      selfHeal: true  # If someone manually edits the cluster, ArgoCD forces it back to match Git
    syncOptions:
      - CreateNamespace=true


Apply this configuration to the cluster:

>> kubectl apply -f cloudbite-argocd-app.yaml

Step 3: The GitOps Workflow in ActionWith that single YAML file applied, your deployment pipeline is now fully automated and self-healing. Here is how your daily engineering workflow operates from this point forward:

Code & Containerize: You write a new feature for the Go checkout service and build the image.

Push to Registry: Your CI pipeline (like GitHub Actions) pushes the new container image to Amazon ECR (Elastic Container Registry).

Update Manifest: The CI pipeline updates the image tag in your deployment.yaml file inside the food_booking_app repository.

ArgoCD Sync: ArgoCD detects the new commit in GitHub. Within 3 minutes, it initiates a rolling update in EKS. It spins up the new Go pods, waits for them to become healthy, and gracefully shuts down the old ones, resulting in zero downtime for users.

The Architecture is Complete
    
